      <hedline>
        <hl1>Decisions at Life's End</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Lori Nigam letter says medical training must include end-of-life care so that young doctors become comfortable with issues (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a medical resident, I have come to realize that all too often, hospital medical staff members play crucial roles on medical teams that people rely upon for advice regarding end-of-life issues for themselves and their loved ones (''Charting a Course of Comfort and Treatment'').</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a medical resident, I have come to realize that all too often, hospital medical staff members play crucial roles on medical teams that people rely upon for advice regarding end-of-life issues for themselves and their loved ones (''Charting a Course of Comfort and Treatment'').</p>
        <p>Education and training regarding end-of-life care must be addressed in the medical school core curriculum, whereby medical students can become comfortable with these issues early in their careers.</p>
        <p>DR . LORI  NIGAM  New York</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
